            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> I thought\r\n> `vim.o.undodir='~/.vim/undodir'` was the equivalent to `set undodir=~/.vim/undodir`, instead of `set undodir='~/.vim/undodir'`\r\n\r\noops, right. \r\n\r\n `vim.o` essentially does the equivalent of `:let &undodir='...'`, which is the \"same as Vim\" case I was thinking of.\r\n\r\n    nvim -u NONE +\"let &undodir='~/.vim/undodir'\" +\"set undofile\"\r\n\r\nSo it still isn't technically a bug but it is a suboptimal interface.\r\n\r\nAlso happens with `:lua vim.opt.undodir='~/.vim/undodir'`. Why do we have 3 different APIs that are half-broken? :facepalm:",
